ЧўEarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/README.mdў@650d999aa34f9d385879a2d9297876b31e7614171df078358b90ab82a2142223ђIntroductionСєThe Many Parts of NushellЏѕThe Nushell project consists of multiple different repositories and subprojects.

You can find all of them under 
[link: https://github.com/nushell] our organization on GitHub
.
The main Nushell repository can be found 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell] here
. It is broken into multiple crates that can be used as independent libraries in your own project, if you wish so.
The repository of our 
[link: https://www.nushell.sh] nushell.sh
 page, including this book, can be found 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell.github.io] here
.
Nushell has its own line editor which 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/reedline] has its own repository
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nu_scripts] ``nu_scripts``
 is a place to share scripts and modules with other users until we have some sort of package manager.
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nana] Nana
 is an experimental effort to explore graphical user interface for Nushell.
[link: https://github.com/nushell/awesome-nu] Awesome Nu
 contains a list of tools that work with the Nushell ecosystem: plugins, scripts, editor extension, 3rd party integrations, etc.
[link: https://github.com/nushell/showcase] Nu Showcase
 is a place to share works about Nushell, be it blogs, artwork or something else.
[link: https://github.com/nushell/rfcs] Request for Comment (RFC)
 serves as a place to propose and discuss major design changes. While currently under-utilized, we expect to use it more as we get closer to and beyond 1.0.
ТРРЏTitle: Introduction
Path: The Many Parts of Nushell
Content:
The Nushell project consists of multiple different repositories and subprojects.

You can find all of them under 
[link: https://github.com/nushell] our organization on GitHub
.
The main Nushell repository can be found 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell] here
. It is broken into multiple crates that can be used as independent libraries in your own project, if you wish so.
The repository of our 
[link: https://www.nushell.sh] nushell.sh
 page, including this book, can be found 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell.github.io] here
.
Nushell has its own line editor which 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/reedline] has its own repository
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nu_scripts] ``nu_scripts``
 is a place to share scripts and modules with other users until we have some sort of package manager.
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nana] Nana
 is an experimental effort to explore graphical user interface for Nushell.
[link: https://github.com/nushell/awesome-nu] Awesome Nu
 contains a list of tools that work with the Nushell ecosystem: plugins, scripts, editor extension, 3rd party integrations, etc.
[link: https://github.com/nushell/showcase] Nu Showcase
 is a place to share works about Nushell, be it blogs, artwork or something else.
[link: https://github.com/nushell/rfcs] Request for Comment (RFC)
 serves as a place to propose and discuss major design changes. While currently under-utilized, we expect to use it more as we get closer to and beyond 1.0.
ЧўEarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/README.mdў@7bdabe8c242eb4908eafd088b59bd3a682269d59c58387392a798a20b8eb3ac7ђIntroductionСђContributingЏbWe welcome contributions!

[link: #the-many-parts-of-nushell] As you can see
, there are a lot of places to contribute to.

Most repositories contain 
``CONTRIBUTING.md``
 file with tips and details that should help you get started (if not, consider contributing a fix!).
Nushell itself is written in 
[link: https://www.rust-lang.org] Rust
.

However, you do not have to be a Rust programmer to help.

If you know some web development, you can contribute to improving this website or the Nana project.

[link: dataframes.md] Dataframes
 can use your data processing expertise.
If you wrote a cool script, plugin or integrated Nushell somewhere, we'd welcome your contribution to 
``nu_scripts``
 or Awesome Nu.

Discovering bugs with reproduction steps and filing GitHub issues for them is a valuable help, too!

You can contribute to Nushell just by using Nushell!
Since Nushell evolves fast, this book is in a constant need of updating.

Contributing to this book does not require any special skills aside from a basic familiarity with Markdown.

Furthermore, you can consider translating parts of it to your language.
